      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one qualify if they own their home worth more than $2,000?",
          "answer": "Yes, the primary residence is typically exempt from asset limits under Medicaid ICP rules. However, there may be home equity caps that apply. The $2,000 limit refers to countable assets like bank accounts, investments, and additional vehicles."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if our family member can't be the live-in caregiver full-time?",
          "answer": "The caregiver must live in the home but doesn't have to provide all care personally. They need to coordinate services and be available to assist, but can arrange for additional help. They must pass the assessment showing they're willing and able to manage the care arrangement."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long is the waitlist really?",
          "answer": "The program doesn't publish waitlist times, and it varies significantly by region and priority level. Those at highest risk of immediate nursing home placement get priority. Contact your local ADRC for current availability in your specific area."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for this program and Medicaid Long-Term Care at the same time?",
          "answer": "No. Your loved one cannot be enrolled in HCE if they are already receiving services through Florida's Statewide Medicaid Managed Care (SMMC) Long-Term Care program. HCE is intended to provide a financial bridge for caregivers supporting seniors who meet clinical requirements but are not yet receiving comprehensive Medicaid managed care services."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one's needs increase after enrollment?",
          "answer": "The case manager will reassess your loved one's condition and adjust services accordingly. If needs exceed what can be safely provided at home even with HCE support, transition planning to higher levels of care may be necessary."
        },
        {
          "question": "Does the live-in caregiver get paid through this program?",
          "answer": "The program provides support services to help the caregiver arrangement work, but it's not primarily a paid caregiver program. The focus is on preventing nursing home placement through family-based care with professional support services."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my loved one doesn't meet the nursing home level of care in the 701B assessment?",
          "answer": "If your loved one doesn't qualify for nursing home level care, they won't be eligible for HCE. However, they may qualify for other home and community services through Older Americans Act programs or lower-level Medicaid waiver services."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can we get services immediately in a crisis situation?",
          "answer": "The program doesn't specify emergency processing times. If your loved one is being discharged from a hospital or facing immediate nursing home placement, contact your local ADRC immediately to discuss expedited assessment options."
        }
      ],
